# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scim-provisioning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] In computing, a **directory service** or **name service** maps the names of network resources to their respective network addresses.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] It is a shared information infrastructure for locating, managing, administering and organizing everyday items and network resources, which can include volumes, folders, files, printers, users, groups, devices, telephone numbers and other objects.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] A directory service is a critical component of a network operating system.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] A **directory server** or name server is a server which provides such a service.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Each resource on the network is considered an object by the directory server.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Information about a particular resource is stored as a collection of attributes associated with that resource or object.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] A directory service defines a namespace for the network.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] The namespace is used to assign a *name* (unique identifier) to each of the objects.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Directories typically have a set of rules determining how network resources are named and identified, which usually includes a requirement that the identifiers be unique and unambiguous.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] When using a directory service, a user does not have to remember the physical address of a network resource; providing a name locates the resource.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Some directory services include access control provisions, limiting the availability of directory information to authorized users.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Several things distinguish a directory service from a relational database.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Attributes are sometimes multi-valued, allowing multiple naming attributes at one level (such as machine type and serial number concatenation, or multiple phone numbers for "work phone").
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Attributes and object classes are usually standardized throughout the industry; for example, X.500 attributes and classes are often formally registered with the IANA for their object ID.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Therefore, directory applications try to reuse standard classes and attributes to maximize the benefit of existing directory-server software.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Object instances are slotted into namespaces; each object class inherits from its parent object class (and ultimately from the root of the hierarchy), adding attributes to the must-may list.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Directory services are often central to the security design of an IT system and have a correspondingly-fine granularity of access control.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Replication and distribution have distinct meanings in the design and management of a directory service.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Replication is used to indicate that the same directory namespace (the same objects) are copied to another directory server for redundancy and throughput reasons; the replicated namespace is governed by the same authority.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Distribution is used to indicate that multiple directory servers in different namespaces are interconnected to form a distributed directory service; each namespace can be governed by a different authority.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Directory services were part of an Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) initiative for common network standards and multi-vendor interoperability.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] During the 1980s, the ITU and ISO created the X.500 set of standards for directory services, initially to support the requirements of inter-carrier electronic messaging and network-name lookup.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] The Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) is based on the X.500 directory-information services, using the TCP/IP stack and an X.500 Directory Access Protocol (DAP) string-encoding scheme on the Internet.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Open-source tools to create directory services include OpenLDAP, the Kerberos protocol and Samba software, which can function as a Windows domain controller with Kerberos and LDAP back ends.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Administration is by GOsa or Samba SWAT.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Name services on Unix systems are typically configured through nsswitch.conf.
[src:scim-provisioning/directory-service] Information from name services can be retrieved with getent.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:scim-provisioning/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:scim-provisioning/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] In telecommunications, **provisioning** involves the process of preparing and equipping a network to allow it to provide new services to its users.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] In National Security/Emergency Preparedness telecommunications services, *"provisioning"* equates to *"initiation"* and includes altering the state of an existing priority service or capability.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] The concept of **network provisioning** or **service mediation**, mostly used in the telecommunication industry, refers to the provisioning of the customer's services to the network elements, which are various equipment connected in that network communication system.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Generally in telephony provisioning this is accomplished with network management database table mappings.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] It requires the existence of networking equipment and depends on network planning and design.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] In a modern signal infrastructure employing information technology (IT) at all levels, there is no possible distinction between telecommunications services and "higher level" infrastructure.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Accordingly, provisioning configures any required systems, provides users with access to data and technology resources, and refers to all enterprise-level information-resource management involved.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] As its core, the provisioning process monitors access rights and privileges to ensure the security of an enterprise's resources and user privacy.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] As a secondary responsibility, it ensures compliance and minimizes the vulnerability of systems to penetration and abuse.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] As a tertiary responsibility, it tries to reduce the amount of custom configuration using boot image control and other methods that radically reduce the number of different configurations involved.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Discussion of provisioning often appears in the context of virtualization, orchestration, utility computing, cloud computing, and open-configuration concepts and projects.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Once provisioning has taken place, the process of SysOpping ensures the maintenance of services to the expected standards.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Provisioning thus refers only to the setup or startup part of the service operation, and SysOpping to the ongoing support.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] The services which are assigned to the customer in the customer relationship management (CRM) have to be provisioned on the network element which is enabling the service and allows the customer to actually use the service.
