[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Cloud providers have different VM startup performance.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Mobile subscriber provisioning refers to the setting up of new services, such as GPRS, MMS and Instant Messaging for an existing subscriber of a mobile phone network, and any gateways to standard Internet chat or mail services.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] The network operator typically sends these settings to the subscriber's handset using SMS text services or HTML, and less commonly WAP, depending on what the mobile operating systems can accept.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] A general example of provisioning is with data services.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] A mobile user who is using his or her device for voice calling may wish to switch to data services in order to read emails or browse the Internet.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] The mobile device's services are "provisioned" and thus the user is able to stay connected through push emails and other features of smartphone services.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Device management systems can benefit end-users by incorporating plug-and-play data services, supporting whatever device the end-user is using..
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Such a platform can automatically detect devices in the network, sending them settings for immediate and continued usability.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] The process is fully automated, keeping the history of used devices and sending settings only to subscriber devices which were not previously set.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] One method of managing mobile updates is to filter IMEI/IMSI pairs.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Some operators report activity of 50 over-the-air settings update files per second.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] This refers to delivering mobile content, such as mobile internet to a mobile phone, agnostic of the features of said device.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] These may include operating system type and versions, Java version, browser version, screen form factors, audio capabilities, language settings and many other characteristics.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] As of April 2006, an estimated 5,000 permutations were relevant.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Mobile content provisioning facilitates a common user experience, though delivered on widely different handsets.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] Provisioning devices involves delivering configuration data and policy settings to the mobile devices from a central point – Mobile device management system tools.
[src:scim-provisioning/provisioning-technology] When getting a customer online, the client system must be configured.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] One example might be that as a company onboards new employees and separates from existing employees, they are added and removed from the company's electronic employee directory.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SCIM could be used to automatically add/delete (or, provision/de-provision) accounts for those users in external systems such as Google Workspace, Microsoft 365, or Salesforce.com.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Then, a new user account would exist in the external systems for each new employee, and the user accounts for former employees might no longer exist in those systems.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] In addition to simple user-record management (creating and deleting), SCIM can also be used to share information about user attributes, attribute schema, and group membership.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Attributes could range from user contact information to group membership.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Group membership or other attribute values are generally used to manage user permissions.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Attribute values and group assignments can change, adding to the challenge of maintaining the relevant data across multiple identity domains.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The SCIM standard has grown in popularity and importance, as organizations use more SaaS tools.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] A large organization can have hundreds or thousands of hosted applications (internal and external) and related servers, databases and file shares that require user provisioning.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Without a standard connection method, companies must write custom software connectors to join these systems and their Identity Management (IdM) system.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SCIM uses a standardised API through REST with data formatted in JSON or XML.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The first version, SCIM 1.0, was released in 2011 by a SCIM standard working group organized under the Open Web Foundation.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] In 2011, it was transferred to the IETF, and the current standard, SCIM 2.0 was released as IETF RFC in 2015.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SCIM 2.0 was completed in September 2015 and is published as IETF RFCs 7643 and 7644.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] A use-case document is also available as RFC 7642.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The standard has been implemented in various IdM software.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The standard was initially called ***Simple Cloud Identity Management*** (and is still called this in some places), but the name was officially changed to *System for Cross-domain Identity Management (SCIM)* when the IETF adopted it.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Interoperability was demonstrated in October, 2011, at the Cloud Identity Summit, an IAM industry conference.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] There, user accounts were provisioned and de-provisioned across separate systems using SCIM standards, by a collection of IdM software vendors: Okta, CyberArk, Ping Identity, SailPoint, Technology Nexus and UnboundID.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] In March 2012, at IETF 83 in Paris, interoperability tests continued by the same vendors, joined by Salesforce.com, BCPSoft, WSO2, Gluu, and Courion (now SecureAuth) nine companies in total.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SCIM is the second standard for exchanging user data, but it builds on prior standards (e.g.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SPML, PortableContacts, vCards, and LDAP directory services) in an attempt to be a simpler and more widely adopted solution for cloud services providers.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The SCIM standard is growing in popularity and has been adopted by numerous identity providers as well as applications.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] As adoption of the standard grows, so do the number of tools available.
[src:scim-provisioning/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The standard leverages a number of open-source libraries to facilitate development and testing frameworks ensure that endpoint's compliance with the SCIM standard.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:scim-provisioning/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
